Title: President
Description:
Ron Arnason, President

Ron Arnason achieved a Bachelor of Science degree in Agriculture in 1976 and a Masters of Business Administration degree in 1980, both from the University of Manitoba.  He has over 30 years experience as a manager and owner in the feed and livestock industry.  Ron was a partner and a senior manager of the Landmark Feeds Group and became president of Landmark Feeds Inc. in 1997.  After the company was acquired by Maple Leaf Foods, Ron served on the Maple Leaf Foods Executive Council.  Ron assumed the additional role of President of Elite Swine Inc. before retiring from Maple Leaf Foods in 2005.  Ron served as a Director of the Animal Nutrition Association of Canada for several years, finally serving as its Chairman in 2001-02.

Title: Exploration Manager
Description:
Andrew Bullock

Mr. Bullock has been involved for 25 years in successful exploration, development, and acquisition ventures throughout Western Canada and the Canadian frontiers. He brings to the company a working knowledge of a wide repertoire of play types in a variety of geological settings. He graduated from McMaster University in 1981 with a Bachelor of Science Honors Degree in Geology, and is a member of APEGGA. Most recently (2001-2004) Mr. Bullock was the G&G Supervisor responsible for directing the exploration and development strategy in ConocoPhillips' West Central, Alberta , region. Targets were met every year primarily as a result of the drilling over 150 wells during his tenure, targeting more than 10 stratigraphic horizons, ranging from the Devonian Leduc through to the shallow Horseshoe Canyon/Scollard Formations. He has gained valuable experience in his career with Dome, Amoco, and Petrostar Petroleum, as well as Crestar Energy.

Title: Program Chair, Chemistry
Description:
Hi Warren - following up on your note below.  Thank you again for passing our name along to your contact.  Also, we wish you the best in establishing a science degree at RDC.  Per our discussion, we prefer to staff our labs with people who are comfortable and interested in living in smaller centers - away from the large cities.  Therefore, if we can tap into RDC students who share a common interest then we would be happy to find placements for them.

Please keep us posted on your developments.

Cheers :)

Chris



Warren Elgersma wrote:

We are also exploring the opportunity to offer a science degree at RDC in collaboration with another institution. Description:
Daniel Andrews, Ph.D., is a Water Quality Specialist with 19 years of experience. He has extensive experience in the oil sands, pulp and paper and mining industries where he served as principal investigator in numerous environmental effects monitoring and environmental impact studies. His principal areas of expertise include:

    * Water and sediment quality
    * Lake acidification and sediment contamination
    * Sediment and water toxicity
    * Environmental effects monitoring
    * Environmental impact assessment
    * Delineation of effluent plume dispersion
    * Benthic surveys and multivariate analysis of benthic populations
    * Bioavailability and environmental fate of aquatic contaminants

Title: CEO
Description:
Ms. Carin combines a background in technical design and commercialization, science and business with over 24 years experience in management and innovation.  Ms. Carin is the Chair of our Board and Chief Executive Officer, having held those positions since she founded EarthRenew in December 1999 and was our Chief Financial Officer from December 1999 to September 2007.  Ms. Carin is the primary inventor and continues to be the main developer of our technologies.  With her business development expertise, she leads the EarthRenew team in all aspects of product, process and equipment technology developments, commercialization, diversification, and adaption. 

In addition, Ms. Carin provides direction in corporate and financial strategies, providing an innovative work environment for a creative and talented team.  From 1993 to 1999, prior to founding EarthRenew, Ms. Carin was a consultant providing financial, business development and management services for a number of firms in British Columbia and Alberta including food and agriculture, livestock, manufacturing, hospitality and air transport.  Services included strategic planning, corporate restructuring, technology commercialization, financing, mergers and acquisitions.  From 1988 to 1992, Ms. Carin founded and headed a full service architectural and engineering firm in the Vancouver area providing services to governments and private sector clients throughout British Columbia, Canada.  Special projects included engineering designs for hospitals for hazardous and recycling waste management programs.  From 1981 to 1985, she was founder and President of a computer graphics firm in North Vancouver, providing innovative computer graphics services and established remote timeshare CADCAM services for engineering and architectural design firms in the Vancouver area.  Ms. Carin served for seven years as a board member and four years as Vice Chair with the Emily Carr University of Art + Design in Vancouver, British Columbia.  Ms. Carin holds a Master of Business Administration (Honors) degree in International Business from Asia Pacific International Institute (New Zealand), and a Bachelor of Fine Arts (Honors) degree from the University of British Columbia.

Title: COO
Description: Dr. Fedkenheuer has over 30 years experience in management in soil and environmental sciences.  Dr. Fedkenheuer has been our President since July 2004 and our Chief Operating Officer since September 2004.  He has been a director of EarthRenew since May 2000.  Over this period Dr. Fedkenheuer managed and contributed to our intellectual property development in both technology and product refinements.  His expertise extends to strategic planning, host development, permitting and regulatory affairs as well as leading the development of marketing and sales and product R&D strategies.  From 1990 to 1999, Dr. Fedkenheuer was a Senior Environmental Scientist and from 1982 to 1989 he was a Senior Environmental Specialist at TransCanada Pipelines, Ltd. (formerly NOVA Corporation) in Calgary, Alberta, Canada.  From 1980 to 1982 Dr. Fedkenheuer was Head, Land Reclamation, Environmental and Social Affairs with Canstar Oil Sands Ltd., Calgary, Alberta and from 1976 to 1980, a Reclamation Research Scientist with Syncrude Canada Ltd. Edmonton, Alberta.  Dr. Fedkenheuer co-founded ALCLA Native Plant Restoration Inc. in 1992.  He also founded the Canadian Native Plant Centre, a not-for-profit company with which he presently acts as President and Chairman.  Dr. Fedkenheuer has served as an Assistant Professor at Lakehead University, Ontario and as an active guest lecturer at the University of Alberta and Montana State University.  He currently serves as an Adjunct Associate Professor in the Faculty of Environmental Design at the University of Calgary.  Dr. Fedkenheuer holds a Ph.D. in Forest Ecology from the University of Minnesota as well as a Master of Science degree in Forest Soils and a Bachelor of Science degree in Agriculture from the University of Wisconsin.

Gary M. Poirier

VP Production

Mr. Poirier was appointed to the position of Vice-President, Production in 2004. Prior to this appointment, Mr. Poirier was Manager of Operations and Engineering at Fairborne since May 1, 2002.

Prior to joining Fairborne Energy, Mr. Poirier held senior management positions with Dominion Energy Canada Ltd. and Mobil Oil Canada. From August 2000 to April 2002, Mr. Poirier was operations manager at Dominion Energy Canada Ltd. From March 1997 to July 2000, Mr. Poirier was business unit manager for the Yellowhead and Eastern business units of Mobil Oil Canada. Mr. Poirier has 16 years of field operational, engineering and exploitation experience in every area of the Western Canadian Sedimentary Basin.

Mr. Poirier graduated in 1988 from the University of Regina with a Bachelor of Applied Science degree in Systems Engineering and is a member of the Association of Professional Engineers, Geologists and Geophysicists of Alberta (APEGGA), Association of Professional Engineers and Geoscientists of British Columbia (APEGBC) and the Society of Petroleum Engineers (SPE).

Title: Senior Water Specialist
Description:
WorleyParsons Komex (formerly Komex International Ltd.) is a consulting engineering firm that specializes in environmental projects. The company is a subsidiary of Sydney, Australia-based WorleyParsons Ltd., which has over 13,500 employees serving clients around the world from over 73 offices in 33 countries. The parent company is a leading provider of engineering services to the energy, resource and industrial sectors.

WorleyParsons' growth in recent years has been considerable. Our expertise spans a range of sectors including: Hydrocarbons, Minerals and Metals, Infrastructure and Power. 

WorleyParsons provides services for the full spectrum of a project's life from concept selection to front-end and detailed design on behalf of a blue chip customer base. The WorleyParsons Group commenced operations over 25 years ago and now employs 23,800 personnel in 84 office locations in over 32 countries. 

WorleyParsons has an established track record of successfully executing major projects for its customers, particularly in the oil and gas industry. Project revenue has been a significant driver of growth. It is complemented by alliance-based revenue, which is generally characterized by longer term relationships with reimbursible costs and performance incentives. 

WorleyParsons' business includes investment in, and development of, niche infrastructure projects, such as remote power generation plants and associated natural gas pipelines.

Title: Manager, Exploitation
Description:
Brian Ritchie - Manager, Exploitation

Mr. Ritchie has over 14 years of oil and gas experience throughout Western Canada. His career began with Imperial Oil, where he held positions in reservoir and production engineering, with a 3 year term in the field. In 2000, Mr. Ritchie joined Anderson Exporation/Devon Canada as an Exploitation Engineer in the Peace River Arch, where his prime focus was the massive 1.9 Tcf Dunvegan Debolt Gas pool, where his team drilled over 40 wells and increase production adding by over 50 mmcf/d. Enviro-Pad?s? design and manufacture heavy-duty portable containment systems for the prevention of ground and surface water contamination. These patented systems provide a proactive solution for primary and secondary containment problems associated with hazardous fluids and chemicals.

Company History:
Enviro-Pads Containment Systems Inc. was founded in 1999 and based in Red Deer, Alberta. Company founder Eric Wassick has been associated with the oilfield industry since 1978 and has extensive working knowledge in international land and offshore drilling exploration. Eric recognized the problems, challenges, and concerns companies are faced with regarding ground and surface water contamination. In order to protect the environment and industry from environmental liabilities the Enviro-Pads were designed, built, and field-tested.

Product Line:
? Hazardous Materials Storage Containment Building
? Wellhead Containment
? Rig Containment
? Wash Pad Containment
? Aircraft Containment

Enviro-Pads portable containment systems are constructed out of high-grade steel, aluminum, or stainless steel and can withstand surface weights up to 30 ton per pad. Each pad interlocks together building continuous containment. Flow hoses connect each pad providing maximum fluid volume storage. Ramps are attached for equipment to be driven on and off. Forklift tubes and lifting eyes are installed for easy handling and setup. Wash walls, recycle equipment, and buildings are optional features.

Objective:
Provide's a proactive solution in the prevention of ground and surface water contamination. Enviro-Pads Containment Systems are completely portable, re-useable, eliminates reclaimation costs and environmental concerns. We are proud to supply industry with an alternative that alleviates the concern of environmental spills, increased productivity, and demonstrates environmental stewardship.

Mission Statement:
Providing proactive solutions for the containment of hazardous fluids while being aware of the climatic, economic, and environmental concerns dealing with the fragile balance between industry and nature.

Seneca Plant 
As part of optimising Orica?s North American operations it has been decided to close the Seneca Ammonium Nitrate (AN) plant.
Orica will continue to supply customer requirements for ammonium nitrate from its world scale AN facility in Alberta, Canada; from long term purchase and toll arrangements; and from its joint venture Ammonium Nitrate company, Geneva Nitrogen Inc. in Utah.


Estimated closure costs of A$9 million (post tax) and site remediation costs of A$22 million (post tax), after deducting estimated future sale proceeds, will be recognised as individually significant items in Orica?s financial statements for the year ending 30 September 2006. Once remediation is complete the site will be sold.

Title: B.Sc., R.P. Bio # 705, Principal
Description: Rupert Wong is a professional biologist who has lived and worked as an independent consultant in the Comox Valley since 1996. His 15 years of experience include a broad range of projects involving ecological assessments and habitat evaluation work in more than 30 watersheds on Vancouver Island and Queen Charlotte Islands. He has experience in site inventories, design and implementation of habitat restoration and compensation works. Rupert is a competitive paddler and recently travelled to Hawaii and New Caledonia in the French Polynesia to compete for Team Canada� he also likes to ski.

Warren has over twelve years experience as a biologist, working primarily in land-use planning, environmental impact assessment (EIA), habitat enhancement and restoration, ecological design, watershed planning, construction monitoring, and water quality and hydrometric assessment throughout BC.

In addition to providing a wide range of services for engineering firms, First Nations, local, federal and provincial government, independent power producers, and private developers, he has amassed considerable experience in a wide variety of community planning initiatives as both a consultant and volunteer.

He has also worked extensively creating GIS-based mapping products for a diverse array of projects.

Warren plays guitar and sings in the �locally famous� band Vitamin L, rides his bikes, and plays center for the Plumbers Old-timers Hockey team. Rupert convinced Warren to become a professional biologist way back when�

Title: AScT
Description:
Doug is known throughout Vancouver Island as a resource specialist, having thirty years experience with the Department of Fisheries and Oceans. Much of this time with DFO was in the Habitat Management Section on Vancouver Island.

Doug has dealt with both freshwater and marine projects on the East and West Coast of Vancouver Island, Sunshine Coast as well as freshwater related projects in the central interior of British Columbia. This work included conducting regulatory project reviews, providing recommendations and/or Fishery Act Authorizations for a wide variety of land development proposals, shoreline protection, stormwater management, forestry infrastructure, hydro projects, mining proposals, habitat enhancement proposals, and numerous projects with the agricultural industry. This work has included extensive interaction with all levels of government, the general public, First Nations as well as numerous environmental non government organizations.

Doug is �semi retired� � when he�s not working, he likes to golf, fish, go camping, hunt, and travel.

Jim is the official �jack of all trades� man at Current Environmental � in addition to his first-rate skills as an Environmental Technician, Jim�s the guy we call when we need to figure out how to overcome technical challenges � like how to drill ballast rocks under water.

Jim has over ten years of experience in watershed management and monitoring. He has coordinated and supervised many volunteer-based smolt fence, water quality, stream habitat restoration and fry density sampling projects in the Morrison Creek Watershed.

He is also one of the members of the National Recovery Team for the Morrison Creek Lamprey and was a co-author of the Recovery Strategy for the Morrison Creek Lamprey (Lampetra richardsoni var. marifuga) in Canada.

Eons ago, Jim worked on a large commercial fish hatchery (Quadra Smolts Little Bear Bay) and established an oyster farm on Cortes Island. Jim is an avid naturalist and a cycling, kayaking and alternative power enthusiast � he�s published several letters in Home Power magazine.

Derek Haarsma, President, and Owner-operator of Haarsma Waste Innovations Inc. is a life-long resident and entrepreneur from Vancouver Island. Derek literally grew up in the Waste Management Industry, earning his allowance starting at the young age of 9 working in his father�s garbage company in Victoria.
As with many children Derek did not envision following in his parents �footsteps�. Much to his surprise, not only has Derek built his career in the Waste Management and Recycling sector, he has gained a reputation in the industry as a serious, competitive and highly efficient individual and business operator. As an entrepreneur, Derek understands the importance of streamlining costs for his customers, and creating a fair market within a highly competitive industry.
Married since 1992, and the father of a daughter and son, building with determination and integrity have always been very important. These values are reflected in the news article that gained Nationwide Canadian and U.S. attention, �David Slays Goliath Times Two�.
Derek Haarsma�s quest to ensure ethics within the Waste and Recycling Industry on Vancouver Island came to fruition through the Federal Competition Bureau�s ruling against two of the Waste Industry�s giants. --------------------
Happy New Year!

For the past 3 years we have been presenting to the Canadian Bar Association, Alberta Southern Division, on our tracking and predicting of the demise of many Agricultural Producers & Services Providers who either through willful blindness, or perhaps through simply bad advice, were quite aware and willing to pass along livestock, products, property or water crops knowing them to be contaminated with E.Coli O157:H7. 

Now with Canada's single largest historic recall of Food Products taking pace last fall, with Health Canada pegging the annual cost for treatment for E.COli O157:H7 related illnesses in Canada at $250M, with new legislation permitting direct trace back to the producer of the animal which introduced this pathogen to air, water, soil, beef or leafy green produce, and with Agricultural Insurance Companies now denying "food-recall" insurance or "general liability" based on this willful blindness, the financial impact of 7+ class action lawsuits in Canada is starting to be felt. 

We will be presenting a review of those Class Actions and what we see as the "Forgotten Liabilities" in these Class Actions to the CBA, Southern Division in Calgary at their Calgary Offices at noon on Tuesday January 22, 2013.

As this will likely be a lively event, we welcome your participation. We will be exploring the other possible Causes of Action and other Defendants who we feel are clear targets given the history, management and control of E.Coli O157:H7 in Canadian Livestock Populations. If you are interested please register via the CBA Web Site: http://www.cba.org/pd/details_en.aspx?id=AB_SCIV22113

Sincerely,

Chris Bolton, B.A.(Hons.), LL.B.

Description:
Meet Councillor Heather Davies
Heather Davies was first elected to Chestermere Town Council in October 2001 and on multiple occasions has served as Deputy Mayor and Acting CEO. 

Background 
Heather's background in Business Education and her extensive work experience in Legal, the Oil & Gas Industry and Business College Administration have made her a strong member of Council. 

Growing up on the northern Saskatchewan/Manitoba boarder, Chestermere Lake seemed to be a natural choice for lake lovers to migrate to!  Heather and her family have been residents of Chestermere for over two decades, now, and still love it! 

Current Committees & Boards 
Audit Committee
Calgary Regional Partnership
Cenotaph Committee (alternate)
Community Health Services Committee
Inter-municipal Planning Committee

Lakefront Owners Association

Ducks Unlimited Canada
Family and Community Support Services
Intermunicipal (Rockyview & Calgary)
Awards & Medals Earned

2000 - Town of Chestermere Volunteer of the Year Award for the many hours dedicated on community committees, but especially for chairing the Weed & Water Committee [now known as the Chestermere Watershed Committee.]
2003 - Commemorative Medal of the Queen's Golden Jubilee Award for her leadership role in spearheading and gathering the necessary scientists and Inter-Governmental Agencies needed to document, evaluate and develop a resolution for Chestermere Lake's weed issues. Her unswerving determination and hard work resulted in the formation of: the Chestermere Working Group; the completion of the Shepard Wetland Stormwater Diversion Project; and the proposed sedimentation removal (dredging) project for Chestermere Lake. 
2010 - Ducks Unlimited Canada Outstanding Achievement Recognition for founding and Chairing the Chestermere Chapter of Ducks Unlmited Canada, which raises funds for local wetland protection and restoration.

Title: Founder and Manager - "King of Pot"
Description:
Mr. Sam Mellace is the founder and manager of New Age Medical Solutions Inc. A company that he hopes someday will be granted authorization to grow marijuana and provide alternative forms of consuming marijuana for other patients. However, Mr. Mellace is unable to give any of the cream or butter to patients as Health Canada has stated that any extractions are outside the scope of the MMAR and thus not protected by the Authorization to Possess.

Samuel Mellace is one of Canada�s longest standing medical marijuana activists, and for the past decade has been actively fighting for a patient�s right to medicate without the addiction, organ failure and death caused by opiates. He is a cancer and car accident survivor who uses cannabis to ease symptoms associates with a liver condition that developed as a result of his deleterious opiate-based pain treatment regime. He is a federally licensed designated grower who grows for himself and his wife and he assists other patients through the onerous exemption process by helping match patients with designated growers.

Sam is also known as one of the most accomplished and sophisticated medical marijuana growers in the world. Labeled by National Geographic�s Lisa Ling as the �King of Pot�, Sam�s high-security medical marijuana production facility has been featured in countless documentaries and publications, including the National Geographic�s most popular documentary �Marijuana Nation�, the CBC�s �Cannabiz�, and many others.

Sam has always promoted safer methods of ingestion to smoking. With a sophisticated laboratory capable of extracting the various cannabinoids without the use of solvents or adulterants, Sam has developed a trans-dermal cream, by adding extracted THC and CBD to moisturizing lotions that he says is an effective treatment for arthritis. He also developed his flagship butter, made from the cannabinoids, which can be safely and effectively used in anything from baked goods to spaghetti sauces.

Title: CEO & President
Description:
Renny Bidinot has over 29 years of experience as CEO and President in the electronic manufacturing and distribution industry. Mr. Bidinot has supplied the Government of Canada with computer peripherals since 1986 through his company Simple Technology Inc. Simple Technology has become the largest supplier of custom language keyboards in Canada, supplying 95% of all requirements to OEM manufacturers.

Also as President and CEO, Renny established Vecture Inc., in Concord, Ontario. Vecture is a design and manufacturing facility of protection circuitry for battery management systems utilized in portable medical, military, and select industrial markets. Renny has also consulted in the manufacturing sector, to streamline production optimizing productivity, while improving overall company morale.

Laboratory Testing
We have on-site microbiology, chemical and analytical laboratories to aid in ensuring our facility remains biologically free of contaminants. Real-time lab results can ensure our pharmaceutical standards are constantly maintained.

On site testing is especially important for harvesting a world class product. There is a week-long window to harvest when cannabinoid levels peak as THC begins to convert to an undesirable form and CBD levels shift. With on site laboratory we can take multiple samples throughout this time frame and get instant results to determine the ideal harvest time. Cannabis harvested earlier in this time frame will have different effects than cannabis harvested later. This is something not achievable with simple visual inspection and even with 3rd party testing that takes days or weeks to get test results.

and is currently working with a cosmetics company.

Have a great day Chris, and a great evening Scott!

Steve

June 13.  Skype call with Scott.
I just talked to Scott.  I will go through points 1 to 6 again and give his comments.  The exec summary is that he wants the Dealers License and is excited about how that may work with a future plan to convert flower to extract to drug delivery system (the "bakery" idea).  He wants Benchmark as an equity partner, as opposed to hiring us.  He wants to put TheraCann back on the table however, as that is what he has been talking up in Europe.  He says he has groups waiting for a business plan, and needs it soon as he is only there for 4 more days. He says he can raise a lot of dough quickly, but needs a document with numbers and projections.

1. I would love to get Sante Veritas signed up as a Benchmark client.
Perhaps another email to him (CC Scott McKinley), outlining our
capabilities would be timely.

Scott says he will insist to Donovan that Sante Veritas sign us up.


2. My guess is that this research opportunity may reappear later in the game,
once Sante Veritas is fully funded. It is probably not something to
push hard right away.

This will likely form part of the DL application.


3. Scott says he really wants the dealers license.  I will ping him
and remind him to fill out the paperwork you sent.

Scott wants to go hard on the dealers license and wants to retain Benchmark to help him
do that.  He says the DL is 95% complete and he just needs help getting it over the
finish line.  He wants Benchmark to have an equity stake.  This likely means that he
does not want to put cash into the application process, but you will have to talk to him
to see how this would work.

Scott is not interested in raising money for a lot of LP's, but says TheraCann
and the bakery business are where he would want to put any money he raised.

June 15 Scott received the TheraCann biz plan and will call with any questions he may have. He is going to Paris tomorrow to meet with people with money. He says Donovan may be intimidated by Benchmark and regards Sante Veritas as his baby. Scott said he is raising money for Sante Veritas and will attempt to convince Donovan to use us. He says he may try to arrange a conference call. To chat about what, I don't know, as we have already given a lot of info to Donovan.

Karen Fruitman is an associate at Magellan Law Group. Karen specialises in business law. Her areas of practice include: corporate, commercial and trust law.

Karen�s legal experience extends to a wide range of business law matters including: business structures, corporate governance, purchase and sale of businesses, corporate reorganizations, employment agreements, shareholder agreements, lease agreements and a wide range of other corporate and commercial issues.

Karen was born and raised in Victoria, British Columbia where she studied Political Science and Japanese Studies at the University of Victoria.  In 1993 she left Victoria to attend the University of Western Ontario Law School where she met her husband and Magellan partner, Steve Fruitman.  She articled at a small law firm in Hamilton, Ontario where she stayed upon her call to the Bar in 1999 to start a litigation practice.  She practised in the areas of personal injury insurance litigation and family law until leaving full time practice to start a family.  She didn�t leave the law behind for long and when her first child was a mere three months old, she started working for a legal publisher summarizing legal judgments for a computerized legal database.

Karen continued to work as a researcher and writer while raising her two children, summarizing cases as well as writing for an Immigration Law reference manual and Halsbury�s Laws of Canada, the definitive general reference to Canadian law.

Karen has assisted Steve in his corporate practice since Magellan opened its doors in August 2011 and received her Practice Certificate from the Law Society of British Columbia in October, 2013.  Steve and Karen share the same vision for a holistic approach to the provision of legal services and her skills and experience as a researcher make her an invaluable addition to Magellan�s business law practice.

Karen shares Steve�s love of cycling and has also participated in the B.C. Lung Association�s Bicycle Trek for Life & Breath, a 200 km ride through the Fraser Valley. Marc is otherwise known as Bubbleman.  He was a big player in cold water extraction.  Steve met him in the 90's.  He is now director of internet sales for Fresh Headies

Purpose: Discuss industrial cold water extractions. 

Marc (currently living in Lions Bay, B.C.), started by giving some history of Bubble Bags and Fresh Headies. Back in the 90's he started manufacturing bubble bags for ice water extractions, but ran into legal trouble with the patent holder, Reinhardt Delp. After 8 years of litigation he came to terms with Mr. Delp and began to license his patents. Marc is currently working with Reinhardt and another partner to come up with industrial sized systems for ice water extraction. He estimates this will be ready in 6 months. At present he is doing extractions out of a facility in Harborside CA. He says the methodologies have been developed, but it is not yet certified food grade.
He has a lot of projects on the go, and we touched on a few:
1. He is trying to license his ice water extraction technology, and the brand "Bubbleman", to L.P.'s. 
2. He has a very large project in Jamaica, in which SYSTEM software would be a good fit.
3. He could use SYSTEM in other applications.
4. He is working with Tony Verzura and Ernie Blackman of United Cannabis http://www.unitedcannabis.us/. They have created a unique extraction technology that is solventless and does not use CO2. It is called Prana, and the website is http://www.actnowprogram.com/pranaoverview/
5. There is currently an L.P. for sale in Canada going for 5-8 million, and they are thinking of buying it.
